This paper is likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) category as it proposes a new algorithm for deep reinforcement learning that leverages small sets of demonstration data to accelerate the learning process. It also involves supervised classification of the demonstrator's actions, which is a common technique in machine learning. 

The paper also involves robotics (cs.RO) as it discusses the applicability of deep RL to real-world tasks, where the agent must learn in the real environment. 

Computer Vision (cs.CV) is another likely category as the algorithm is applied to 42 games, which likely involve visual input. 

Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) is also a possible category as the paper involves developing an algorithm that can learn from both demonstration data and experience. 

Finally, the paper may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) category as it discusses the challenges of applying deep RL to real-world tasks and the need for algorithms that can learn from small amounts of data.
